{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580345/1945122701/0386.xml":{"full_text":"Page\ni\nI\nI\n1\n1\nU\nn\no\no\nI\n4\nt!\na\n..tt\nJi\nei\nw\ntc\ntl\ntc\nai\nsc\nal\ntt\nim\nvi\nBl\nj3\nta\nis\nAi\u00bb\nal\nu\nKI\no\nii\nE\ntl\nu\n4\npreviously attained from one calendar\nyear to the tiext.\u201d\n\u201cVast AccumutafM DvMAhd\u201d\nThe corporation anticipates an\nover 1945 in nonresidentlal construc\ntion, with substantial increases in\nincrease next year of 20 percent\npublic and religious buildings in this\nclassification. An increase of 178 per\ncent in residential construction, with\na total of $1,350,000,000 in the east\nern states is estimated. One- and\ntwo-family house construction will\ndominate residential building in 1946,\nthe report states.\nPotential demands is \"generally con\niidered so large that it is likely to\nrequire construction, over an extended\nperiod, in larger amounts than in any\nprevious peacetime years.\n\u201cThere is plenty of factual evidence\nof a vast accumulated demand in the\nform of estimated shortages, contem\nplated and planned construction 'proj\nects running into many billions of dol\nlars, announced expansion and rehabi\nlitation programs of industries, com\nmercial organizations, utilities, state\nand local governments,\u201d the corpora\ntion points out.\nAt the same time, it says 3 kinds\nof retarding factors exist to delay re\nf. vivai. These are increased costs and\ncurrent confusion about market con\nditions, continuing government con\ntrols so far as prices and rents are\nconcerned, and the growing pains of\nan industry called upon to expand its\noperations very suddenly.\nManpower Still ScsW#'\nManpower in the designing, build\ning, and materials and equipment\nfields is still comparatively scarce,\nbat according to Dodge\u2019s interpreta\ntion this condition is not likely to last\nvary long.\nPresent conditions with respect to\nmaterials and manpower do not sug\ngest any ultimate limit on the capac\nity of the industry,\u201d the study says,\n*,\u2018\u201cThey do indicate, however, a moder\nate speed of expansion in the transi\ntion year 1946.\u201d\nLegal Analysis\nfCesrias/d Frew Pet? Owe/\nof today's strikes: the increase\nthe cost of living which the govern\nment itself has estimated as 88%.\nDuring the, war increased take-home\nthrough overtime pay was a mitigat\ning factor when the War Labor Board\nrefused to recommend to the Presi\ndent a wage policy baaed on the ac\ntual increase in living, coats. Today,\nhowever, this factor no longer exists\nand, the wage increases for which la\nbor by reason of its no-strike pledge\nwas unable to fight during the war\nhave become an urgent necessity for\nwhich Workers must fight.\nClearly, if the causes of strikes are\neconomic in nature, it is absurd to\nplace limitations upon the right to\nprotest against these causes. Even\nif the blame rested with labor, cool\ning-off provisions are an ineffectual\nway of preventing strikes. New Zeal\nand Australia and Canada have en\njoyed nd unusual industrial bliss\nthrough their statutory limitations on\nstrikes, nor have those of our states\nlike Kansas and Colorado which have\ntried such experiments been more suc\ncessful.\nConsideration as well as passage\nof the Norton bill can only block sober\nexamination of the real causes of labor\ndisputes. Let no one be fooled by its\napparent mildness.\nDodge Corporation Sees\nConstruction For Next Year\nRising Fifty Percent Over 1945\nNew York City\u2014(ILNS).\u2014Even in tlie face of present re\ntarding factors, F. W. Dodge Corporation, fact-finding organiza\ntion for employers in the construction industry, estimates total\ndollar volume of new construction next year as 50 percent great\ner than in 1945 in the 37 states east of the Rocky Mountains.\nThe estimate for all construction in the states is $4,750,\n000,000 against $3,160,000,000 expected for 1945 on the basis of\nthe record for the first 10 months of this year.\n\u201cIn dollars, this volume is greater than that of the years im\nmediately preceding the war,\u2019\u2019 the corporation declares. \u201cTaking\n'cost increases into account, it represents a physical volume some\nwhere between that of 1939 and 1940. The percentage increase is\nabout1 as high as the highest ever*\u2014 -----------------\u2014r-\nin\nAccident Rise Dedared\nPeril To U. S. Welfares\nNew York City\u2014(ILNS). Wide\nspread increases in accidents threaten\nthis country with an economic and fi\nnancial emergency, Ned H. Dearborn,\npresident of the National Safety\nCouncil, declared at a luncheon in the\nHotel Waldorf-Astoria. He forecast a\nhuge loss in 1946 through preventable\nmishaps.\n\u201cEstimates based upon statistics\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cindicate that 1 out of every 14\npersons in the United States will be\ntajured in accidents next year. The\nwastage will be equivalent to about\nthe amount required to service the\nS national debt, or $5,000,000,000. Unless\nwe curb the accident rate, economic\nreconversion will be seriously impaired\nand large-scale unemployment will re\nsuit.*___ ______________________\nALWAYS USE\nCREAM TOP\nMilk BoHlf\nran\nam\nurtTAM\nDW CaolMsfoalr 9y\nPrice Fixing Act\nfCes/tmcrd From Paffe One)\nlent to such products by branding,\nnational advertising, etc., and In part\nto the existence of strong cooperating\ntrade groups of manufacturers, whole\nsalers and retailers.\nThe FTC names the Natl. Assin, of\nRetail Druggists, \u201cand its affiliated\nstate and local organizations\u201d as hav\ning \u201cadvised druggists to support\nand push the sale of price-maintained\nbrands (at higher mark-ups) and to\ndo (he opposite respecting non-price\nmaintained brands have written\nthreatening letter* and published\nthreatening articles in the trade press\ndirected to manufacturers who re\nfrained from placing their products\nUnder resale price maintenance, or\nwho failed to enforce their prices to\nthe satisfaction of retailers.\nThe retail drug lobby recommends\na markup of 33 1-3% on selling price,\nor 50% over cost, for retailers and\nwhile the manufacturers do not all\ngrant that margin in setting resale\nminimums, the lobby is demanding\npressure from the retailers to reach\nit in all goods.\nWholesalers, coming Tn for a cut of\nthe price melon, have profited through\nthe fixed price law by eliminating\nspecial discounts previously given\nretailers and this, in turn, the FTC\nfinds \u201chas narrowed the retailer\u2019s\nmargin on products affected and\nstimulated their demand for Jjjgher\nminimum resale prices.\u201d f/ Z,\nHITS RETURN OF\nJOB OFFICES TO\nSTATE CONTROL\nWashington, D. C.\u2014(ILNS).\u2014Em\nphasizing that the problem of full em\nployment is serious, with millions of\nveterans and former war workers\nlooking for jobs, the labor committee\nof the National Planning Association\nurged continued federal operation of\nthe U. S. Employment Service. The\ncommittee sharply criticised legisla\ntion for disintegrating the service and\nreturning it ,to state agencies.,\nOrganized labor has taken the same\nstand on operation qf th^ employment\nservice. s\nOffering a 5-point statement of\nprinciples for guidance of the job\nservice system in selecting personnel,\nthat the government has had to take\nover the public employment service\nin every big crisis.\nThe committee urged\n\u201cRigid adherence to a nonpolitical\nservices ystem in selecting personnel,\nwith adequate compensation and civil\nservice rights for all employes.\n\u201cOrganization of the system of local\nemployment offices In a way that\nwill guarantee adequate geographical\ncoverage and sufficient staff and\nequipment in each* local office to serve\nworkers and employers effectively.\n\u201cAdherence to national labor stand\nards, including: A referral policy in\nlocal offices that keeps the employ\nment service from being used to re\ncruit for substandard industries, to\ninduce workers to take substandard\njobs, or to perpetuate economic dis\ncrimination against qualified workers\nfor racial or religious reasons.\n\u201cEstablishment of local advisory\ncommittees so that management, labor\nand the public will be consulted on\nall important matters.\u201d\nCongressional action to break up\nthe USES, the committee stated, was\na \u201cretreat from responsibility\u201d and\nwould turn over the task of the states\nalthough the government would have\nto go on paying the cost.\nDeclaring the labor market is na\ntional, the committed Mdded that dur\ning the wartime employment boom1\nmore than 15,000,000 people mgved\nout of their home counties.\nCompound Intereat and advertbing\nare very similar the longer they are\ncontinued the better are the result*\nCO 00004,\nREAL BARGAINS\n6 Rooms and bath dn Maple\nSt. Price $2600.\n7 Rooms, bath and furnace on\nMulberry St. $3700. i i\n4-family apartment building\n$76.00 a month. Price $6,000. i\non West Eighth St Income\nDouble hogae on Odgen St.\u2014 i i\n4\nrooms each aide, inside toilet\nPrice $26*0.\nDouble House in East Alley\npm*. ,,J\nMUKPHY CRAIG\nREAL ESTATE BROKERS\nJohn Murphy* MBH St Clair\nAve^ Phene MIS.\nCharlee Craig, ISO East Sixth\nSL, Phene 5514.\nlOMMMMIdHNMMMtodMNMMMMMMMH\nThere is a wave of crime rolling\nup and some folks seem to be surpris\ned by it.\nMostly this wave appears to be\ncomposed of what is called juvenile\ndelinquency, although Rome of it\ncomes right close to being grown up\nI viciousness. u\nThere is nothing surprising about\nthe development. It would be surpris\ning if we didn\u2019t have it.\nWe have all of the factors for its\ndevelopment, in heaping up measure.\nWe have vast idleness, including\nthe idleness following demobilization.\nWe have an atmosphere still smok\ning with the ghastly adventure, of the\ngreat war.\nWe have young folks whose nome\nlife has been just about zero, with\nparents working to exhaustion in war\nwork.\nWe have the feeling of \u201cwhat the\nhell\u201d that follows every great war.\nAnd now\nquency.\nWhen we throw away the restraints\nthat make collective living possible\nwe throw away the thing which we\ncall civilization.\n'War is the greatest repudiation of\ncivilization and if we have another\none it will be perhaps the end of civil\nization. y\na--'\nThe business 1 of developing' what\nwe call civilization has been a slow\nbusiness. It is still far from complete.\nToo many who think they are civi\nlized actually are not. And millions\nnever heard the word.\nFrance in the days of \u201clet \u2019em eat\ncake\u201d thought of herself as civilized,\nbut she wasn\u2019t. England, when Dick\nens wrote, would have been shocked\nto be told she wasn\u2019t civilized, but\nshe wasn\u2019t.\nWhen we allowed children to work\nPROGRAM FOR TENANT FARMERS\u2014Meeting fnr their 12th annual\nconvention, Southern Tenant Farmers Union endorsed five-poiht legislative\nprogram to guarantee \u201cfour freedoms of farm labor.\u201d Program includes\nlegislation to relieve distress of workers displactM Ijy mechanical cotton\npickers, provisions for adequate housing and health care, and guaranteed\nannual wage. Current annual, wage of tenant farmer is about $400,\u2014(Fed\nerated Pictures). t'v f,\nTHE CHERRY TREE\nwe have crime\u2014or delin-\nfact that we have what\na crime wave shows us\nNow the\namounts to\nsomething that should make us stop\nand think hard. It should give us\npause, as the book writers sometimes\nput it.\nIt shows us how shallow is the grip\nof civilization upon us. It shows us\nhow easily we sluff off the restraints\nof civilized living.\nCivilized living requires that folks\nbehave decently toward each other.\nIt requires that they do not go around\nrobbing each other, or killing each\nother.\nThere are common rules for living\nthat have grown up out of the experi\nences of the human race. These rules\ncan be broken only at the cost of all\nthat we have learned.\nWe like this time of the year cause we can wish\nyou Joy and Cheer in a good old fashioned way.\nWhat more to there to say, A Happy New Year,\nFolks.. J\u2019'\nFIRST FEDERAL SAVINGS\n.4-\nTTTE POTTKftS\na\u2019\n\u25a0I\n3S?\nin coal mines and in cotton factories,\nwe weren\u2019t civilized, either.\n..\u2022And all of us still have a long road\nto travel, before we achieve what we\ncall true and complete civilization.\nO\nr' But such as we have doesn\u2019t seem\nable to stand many shocks. Thous\nands go haywire when jolted by out\nof-line emotional experiences or by\neconomic shocks.\nWhatever it is that makes us be\nhave, in the mass, doesn\u2019t go very\ndeep.\nViolence is *n evidence of missing\nstitches in the fabric of civilization.\nThat goes for violence of any kind.\nThe hope we have lies in the fact\nthat somehow the majority clings to\nreal values and marches on, bringing\nthe minority into line, pounding home\nthe lesson.\nBut even at that, the fabric of civi\nlization that is stretched over the\nvicious appetites of savagery is, for\nall of us, very thin. We had best\nwatch closely, lest too many fangs\npoke through. Whim too many slip\nback too much we are likely to all\nof us slip a little.. And a good way\nto avoid slipping- anywhere is to re\nmove, so far as possible, the causes\nof\nthe slipping.\u2014CMW.\nJob Opportunity^.\ng-?. (Continued From Page One)\nfrankly admitted that cheap labor was\nits big asset, it would have been near\ner the truth.\nBut the worker* of Winston-Salem\nare fighting hard to break down the\nlow wage system, which gives them\na choice of jobs paying 40c to 60c an\nhour. Leading the campaign for a min\nimum wage law of at least 65c hour\nly in the big FTA local in the city\u2019s\nmain industry. Not only are 100 let\nters a week going from members of\nthe local to their senators and con\ngressmen, but the local is also circu\nlarizing all the farmers and business\nmen of the community, pointing out\ntheir stake in the 65c minimum wage\nlaw.\nTo the farmers the tobacco workers\nsay: \u201cProsperity is like a train.\ntravels on two rails. One is good\nprices to farmers, the other is decent\nwages to workers. The one is no goojJ\nwithout the other.\u201d 4\nTo the small businessmen they are\nsaying: \u201cThe passage of this bill\nwould mean an increase in the buy\ning power of over half the workers\nin Winston-Salem. It would mean\nmore trade for you.\u201d k\nDemand theUnloa LabeL\ny\nM.M..M. -*A--k&. M. M..M M. kA^M Al ML .M.\nWwwWMMMKMMMw\u2019-th\nWFWHMHWWuMM.MMMA1A-H\n\u25baCOMMENT ON WORLD'\nEVENTS.,\nA bright future for the Internationa\nal Labor Organization in cooperation\nwith the United Nations Organization\nis seen by Edward J. Phelan, Inter\nnational Ijibor Office acting director.\nHis opinion goes far to allay appre\nhension that the activities of the In\nternational Labor Organization would\nbe curtailed or hampered by coordina\ntion with the UNO.\nThere is no reason to fear that the\nUnited Nation Organization\u2019s power\nto coordinate the activities of the var\nious specialized intergovernmental\nagencies will be employed to restrict\nthe activities of the international La\nbor Organization, Phelan said at Mon*,\ntreal ILO headquarters follbwirtg hit\nreturn from the recent fLO confer^'\nence in Paris.\nOh the contrary, he.said, the estab\nlishment of the Economic and Sdcial\nCouncil of the United Nations would\nreinforce the ILO \u201cfor it will pro^\nvide the means to secure the appli-*\u2019\ncation of those international measures,\nin the economic and financial fields\nwithout which the II.O\u2019s efforts in\nthe field of international social policy\nmust frequently fail.\u201d\nThe ILO, Phalen emphasized, would\nwelcome the coordination of its ac\ntivities with those of the United Na\ntions and those of the other function\nal international agencies.\n\u201cThe ILO today is ready to negoti\nate with the United Nations, and I\nhave every hope that when the nego\ntiations. take place the results will\nbe satisfactory,\u201d he declared.\n\u201cAs I said in a speech to the Paris\nconference,\u201d he added, \u2018Peace, produc\ntion and social justice are the three\npillars on which the future of the\nworld must be built. To them corres\npond the appropriate niternational in\nstitutions\u2014first, the security machin\nery of the United Nations, second, the\neconomic machinery of the United\nNations, comprising the Economic and\nSocial Council and the group of spec\nialized economic agencies, dealing with\ninternational trade, finance, food and\nagriculture, etc., which it will be itM\nprincipal function to coordinate, andi\nthird, the machinery of the Interna\ntional Labor Organization, whose task I\nit is to promote social justice in full i\ncooperation with other international\nagencies which will be its natural\nallies in this task.\u201d\n'P,\nPhelan called the Paris Conference\none of the most notable of the 27 that\nhave been held since the ILO was|\nestablished (rHe pointed out\nthat 48 coui)|.rigj| participated, the\nlargest number attend a confer\nence since the 1937 session in Geneva.\nNotable, too, he said, was the fact\nthat the delegates and advisers totaled\n470, compared with 860 at the Phila\ndelphia conference in 1944, and 352\nat the last prewar conference in Gen\neva.\nThis wide representation Jwae not\nthe only reason for optimism for, the\nfuture of the ILO, he said.'\n\u201cImportant statements/1, he explain\ned, \u201cwere made, at Paris in behalf, of\nthe United State, British, French, and\nother governments, pledging- .their\nwholehearted- support for the, organ\nization. Thei^ are tniny' reksohs for\nconfidence that, this support \u2018will con\ntinue, There 1|, the fact thit .the ILO,\n\u2022jvith its tripghtite cornpositidns of\ngovernment, management and labor\nrepresentatives, ,is the inevitable iq*\niernationai reflection of., the Whole\ndevelopment of social progress\nIt\u2019s\n0h\u2018.\n\u25a0Av\nho\nfar\nks labor and allied social problems,\nare concerned.\u201d I\n\u2022V\ni*4*\u00bb0t4eltetrio iifM\nCMMMAImu\n1\nThe contract covers all except 3\nof the'major hotels. The exceptions\nare the Waldorf-Astoria, for which\nthe union only recently won bargain\ning rights the Lexington, where ne\ngotiations are in progress and the\nHotel Governor Clinton.\nBesides the wage increases the\nnew contract, which runs until May\n31, 1948, contains a no-strike, no\nlockoUt provision extension of paid\nvacations up to 2 weeks, based on\nlength of service 4 holidays off with\npay or the alternative of double time\na joint employment agency to combat\nfee-charging agencies continuation of\nhealth and accident insurance paid by\nthe employers and a clause barring\ndiscrimination because of race, creed,\ncolor or national origin.\nThe wage provisions were made\nretroactive to June 1, representing\nlump sum payments as high as $271.\n'Buy War Bonds and flwht laflatimi\nVFERCW* KIND SAYS\nHow ls the Timo\nto Buy Gaol\nOtte tn tfawia\nKIND COAL CO.\nRailroad 4 BoUock Streets\nT.\ntG\n/jV\nthe country, sufficient medical service\nfol\" everyone, \u201can efficient military\nintelligence system\u201d and \u201ceternal\nvigilance on the part of the State De\npartment.\u201d\nHe urged that Congressional ac\ntion on peacetime* training be de\nferred until after demobilisation of\nthe armed forces and until the com\npletion of treaties and international\ncommitments \u201cand the outcome of ef\nforts to insure world peace.\u201d\nCalled to follow Hines were offi\ncials of the International Association\nof Machinists, the Brotherhood of\nSleeping Car Porters and the CIO.....\nHotel Employees\nWin Pay Increase*\nNew York City*\u2014 (ILNS)/\u2014 Pdy\nscales of .25,QQ0 union workers em-'\nployed in 140 of the city\u2019s hotels have\nbeen increased from 25 td 40 percent\nunder a new contract just signed by\nthe New York Trades Council, AFL,\nand the Hotel Association of New\nYork.\n.Signing ceremonies book place in\nthe office of Edward P. Mulrooney,\nimpartial chairman of the hotel in\ndustry. The workers were represented\nby Jay Rubin president of the trades\ncouncil.\nV V?\nt\u00a3\nfe-4,\nK\nhS\ni\n**4 \u00bbvw\u00abr\n\u20224\nJ/,\n\u2018u\n\u2022vw\nDraw your own conclusions\na fact.\nAlmost everybody\nAmerica* self-supporting, tax- fi/e Nuorance policy\u2014you ate\npaying electric rompanias. y z included among the fodfreef\nThere are millions of people\non the stockholder lists A 4SYoUr\nowners of this industry. .y-\nA\n\u00abw\n.r t.\nBut even if you\u2019re not ij\nyas have a taaingt aootunt or\n_________ _______ ,______\nssvings banfc And hi?\nthese companies\u2014housewives, sursnee company put your to Next timeyouhear anybody\nfarmers, nurses, teachers,\nmechanics. You may be one of\ntoese many direct owners, -z*- into electric light kttd JtoMror **ber, they\u2019re talking about you/\nThursday, Dccemuor 2?)\nCondemning Draft Proposal\nLabor Asks Name Of Nation\nU. Sb Is Preparing To Fight\nWashington, D. C.^-(ILNS),\u2014Demanding to know whom the\nUnited States is preparing to fight, the representatives of organ\nized labor assailed proposed universal military training legislation\nbefore the House Military Affairs Committee.\nHeading a group of labor spokesmen called to testify, Lewis\nG.- Hines, American Federation of Labor legislative representa\ntive asked the committee: J\"\n\u201cMay we in all fairness ask, preparedness for what? If we\nare on the brink of another war, should we' not have the right to,\ndemand with who, when and where\nHjnes said the AFL believed preparedness should be ifecorfi-\nplished through more adequate physical care for the children of .J\nanffi/iiant rnadipal\ncarvieP\u20191\n94\n1945\nWants Open Shop\n(Continued From Page One)\nSen. W. Lee (Pappy) O\u2019Daniel, Texai\nleader of theChristian Americans,\nhas vainly tried to have the proposi\ntion incorporated as a rider on fed\neral appropriations bills.\nA proposed right-to-work amend\nment to be incorporated into the fed\neral constitution and introduced by\nO\u2019Daniel, has, thus\u2019 far, been pigeon\nholed irf the Senate. The Christian\nAmericans, working closely with\nO\u2019Daniel, have, succeeded, however, in 4\nhaving labor-shackling legislation en\nacted either as statutory measures or\nas state constitutional amendments in\nabout a dozen different states.\nWorking through the top leadership\nof the Florida Farm Bureau F'wlera\ntion, the Christian Americans were\nable to get the open shop amendment\nincorporated into the state constitu- s\ntion at the 1944 election, Watson, who\nis a close friend of CA Exec. Sec.\nVance Muse in Houston, Tex., stumped\nthe state for the amendment.\nThere is still another danger in\nWatson\u2019s proposal for an open shop\nclause in the pending fact-finding leg\nislation, which has been condemned\nby all of organized labor. The danger\nis this\u2014that Truman\u2019s original fact?\nfinding legislation will -be presented.\nby its spdhsors to the American pee\npie as an alternative to the legisla\ntion plus the open shop amendment. I\nWhich would be the old game of hav-\ning Mr. Tweedledum shadow-boat Mr.\nTweediedee, with the corporation*\npulling the wires winning either way.\nS?.\nLA\nH-S\nLIKE A GUIDING\n\\LIGHT\n7^\n.t r.* ..\u2666\u25a0Vi5*'**A\nv?*0ur Service can relieve you\nof all details. No need to worry\nabout funeral arrangements in\ntimes of grief and sorrow.\n2 When tlie need arises, let us\nv.-zn\nDAWSON FUNERAL\ny.,\n\u25a0-\u25a0.\u00ab.^hOME\n815 W. Fifth St.\n7*v.\nk Ii**\"\nr-y\u2019t\ni* w'p\nv\nMe\u2019\nf\u2019 Tx-.\n\u2022IS. f\u2018\nA.\nA-\n:'5AV**\u2022\u25a0'*\u2019\u00ab$\n-.\u2018\u201c\u25a0'i.r- '.'\u2019-e-'g'\u201d\na\nA\n7\nfc A\nJi\n,Pm4\n10\nR-\ntxi\nL.\n\u202241\n4M\na\n\u2019'\u2022Mi\nsecurities. That\u2019s because years\nof dependable service and good\nCusinejs management on the\npart of the electric companie*\nnaw ma4e their securities a\naound investment.